The issue with the current implementation is that it is only searching for the presence of the keywords "TABLE" and "COLUMNS" in the text. However, it is not considering the structure of the text to determine if it represents a table or columns.

To address this issue, we can modify the function to analyze the structure of the text to determine if it represents a table or columns. We can look for patterns such as rows of data with consistent column separators or headers for each column to identify a table or columns.

Let's update the function to implement this improved logic:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  // Split the text into lines
  const lines = text.split('\n').map(line => line.trim());

  // Check if the text represents a table
  if (lines.length >= 3) {
    const headerRow = lines[1].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the second line by multiple spaces
    const dataRow = lines[2].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the third line by multiple spaces
    if (headerRow.length === dataRow.length) {
      return "TABLE";
    }
  }

  // Check if the text represents columns
  const columnHeaders = lines[0].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the first line by multiple spaces
  if (columnHeaders.length > 1) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  }

  // If the text does not match the table or column structure, return "NORMAL"
  return "NORMAL";
}
```

By analyzing the structure of the text data, we can determine whether it represents a table, columns, both, or neither based on the presence of consistent column separators and headers.

The issue with the current implementation is that it is assuming the structure of a table based on the length of lines and the consistency of column headers and data rows. However, the content you provided does not fit into the assumed structure, resulting in an incorrect classification.

To address this issue, we can modify the function to identify a table structure by looking for consistent column separators and headers throughout the text. We should also handle cases where the text might represent a combination of columns and a table.

Let's update the function to implement the improved logic:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  // Split the text into lines
  const lines = text.split('\n').map(line => line.trim());

  // Check if the text represents a table
  if (lines.length >= 3) {
    const firstRow = lines[0].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the first line by multiple spaces
    const secondRow = lines[1].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the second line by multiple spaces
    const thirdRow = lines[2].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the third line by multiple spaces
    if (firstRow.length === secondRow.length && secondRow.length === thirdRow.length) {
      return "TABLE";
    }
  }

  // Check if the text represents columns
  const columnHeaders = lines[0].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the first line by multiple spaces
  if (columnHeaders.length > 1) {
    // Check if the remaining lines also have the same number of columns
    const columnCounts = lines.map(line => line.split(/\s{2,}/).length);
    if (columnCounts.every(count => count === columnHeaders.length)) {
      return "COLUMNS";
    }
  }

  // If the text does not match the table or column structure, return "NORMAL"
  return "NORMAL";
}
```

By analyzing the structure with more comprehensive checks, we can handle cases where the text might represent a table, columns, both, or neither more accurately.
